This pull request adds several improvements to the school activities signup application, focusing on expanding the available activities, enforcing signup rules, and enhancing the user interface to display participant information more clearly.

### Backend enhancements

* Added six new activities to the `activities` dictionary in `src/app.py`, each with a description, schedule, maximum participants, and an empty participant list.
* Improved the signup logic in `src/app.py` to prevent duplicate signups and enforce the maximum participant limit, returning appropriate error messages if violated.

### Frontend improvements

* Updated `src/static/app.js` to display a list of participants for each activity on the activity card, including a message when there are no participants yet.
* Added new CSS styles in `src/static/styles.css` to visually format the participants section within each activity card, making the participant list clearer and more attractive.

# Implement AI-assisted validation and fraud scoring features ## Summary This PR adds comprehensive AI-powered claim processing capabilities to SmartClaims360, including validation, fraud detection, summarization, and routing features. The implementation follows a pluggable architecture with feature flags and mock LLM integration for future extensibility. **Key Changes:** - Added `fraudScore` field to Claim entity (BigDecimal 0..1) - Created new `com.smartclaims360.ai` package with 4 core services - Implemented statistical fraud scoring using z-score analysis and weighted risk factors - Added 4 new REST endpoints for AI-powered claim processing - Comprehensive test suite with 18+ new tests covering unit and integration scenarios - Feature flags in application.yml for enabling/disabling AI services - Updated documentation with API examples and architecture overview **New Endpoints:** - `POST /claims/validate` - Rule-based + AI validation with hints - `POST /claims/score` - Fraud risk scoring (0.0-1.0 scale) - `GET /claims/{id}/summary` - Formatted claim summaries with risk analysis - `GET /claims/{id}/route` - Intelligent routing suggestions based on risk ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human **‚ö†Ô∏è Critical Items (5 items - please verify carefully):** - [ ] **Business Logic Validation**: Verify fraud scoring thresholds (0.7 = high risk, 0.4 = medium) and claim type restrictions (AUTO, HEALTH, PROPERTY, LIFE) match business requirements - [ ] **Security Review**: Confirm that removing `@Valid` annotations from AI controller endpoints doesn't introduce security vulnerabilities (validation now handled by AI service) - [ ] **End-to-End Testing**: Test all 4 new endpoints with various claim scenarios including edge cases (negative amounts, invalid types, missing data) - [ ] **Statistical Algorithm Review**: Validate the fraud scoring algorithm (z-score + weighted factors) produces reasonable results with your test data - [ ] **Performance Testing**: Test with larger datasets to ensure fraud scoring performance is acceptable (currently analyzes all historical claims) **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. pull_request.body:
CLOSES: #330

## Summary
- Implemented DatabaseTransaction utility class for atomic operations
- Automatic transaction support detection with graceful fallback to standalone MongoDB
- Updated all critical multi-write UserService operations to use transactions
- Enhanced User model with session-aware instance methods
- Comprehensive test coverage including unit and integration tests

## Changes Made
### Core Implementation
- **DatabaseTransaction.ts**: New utility class providing MongoDB transaction support
  - `withTransaction()`: High-level transaction wrapper
  - `withSession()`: Manual session management
  - `isTransactionSupported()`: Auto-detection of replica set support
  - `withFallback()`: Graceful degradation for standalone instances

### Database Layer Updates
- **UserServiceDatabase.ts**: All multi-write operations now use transactions
  - `markEmailVerified()`: Atomic email verification + token clearing
  - `updatePasswordAndClearTokens()`: Atomic password reset operations
  - `generateAndSaveResetToken()`: Atomic token generation
  - `generateAndSaveEmailToken()`: Atomic email token generation

### User Model Enhancements
- **User.ts**: Updated instance methods to accept session parameters
  - `generatePasswordResetToken()`: Now supports transactions
  - `generateEmailVerificationToken()`: Now supports transactions
  - `updateLastLogin()`: Now supports transactions

### Service Layer Integration
- **UserServiceAuth.ts**: Enhanced user creation process with atomic operations
  - User creation + email token generation now atomic
  - Improved error handling for transaction failures

### Testing
- **DatabaseTransaction.test.ts**: Comprehensive unit tests with mocking
- **UserServiceTransaction.integration.test.ts**: Real database integration tests
- All existing functionality maintained with backward compatibility

## Benefits
‚úÖ **Data Consistency**: Multiple database writes are now atomic
‚úÖ **Reliability**: No more partial state from failed operations
‚úÖ **Backward Compatibility**: Works with both replica sets and standalone MongoDB
‚úÖ **Error Handling**: Graceful fallback when transactions aren't supported
‚úÖ **Performance**: Minimal overhead with automatic detection
‚úÖ **Test Coverage**: Comprehensive testing of all transaction scenarios

## Test Results
- ‚úÖ All unit tests pass

- ‚úÖ Transaction fallback mechanisms work correctly

pull_request.title: Add registration validation and more activities
pull_request.body:
This pull request adds several improvements to the school activities signup application, focusing on expanding the available activities, enforcing signup rules, and enhancing the user interface to display participant information more clearly.

### Backend enhancements

* Added six new activities to the `activities` dictionary in `src/app.py`, each with a description, schedule, maximum participants, and an empty participant list.
* Improved the signup logic in `src/app.py` to prevent duplicate signups and enforce the maximum participant limit, returning appropriate error messages if violated.

### Frontend improvements

* Updated `src/static/app.js` to display a list of participants for each activity on the activity card, including a message when there are no participants yet.
* Added new CSS styles in `src/static/styles.css` to visually format the participants section within each activity card, making the participant list clearer and more attractive.

issue.body:
The proposal to treat SHA-256 outputs (256-bit strings) as points on a number line‚Äîinterpreting them as large integers from 0 to \( 2^{256} - 1 \)‚Äîand compute discrete derivatives (differences between consecutive hashes) to identify patterns is an intriguing application of discrete analysis to cryptographic outputs. This aligns with differential cryptanalysis techniques, where differences in outputs are examined for non-random behaviors, though SHA-256 is engineered for uniformity and resistance to such structure. To explore this rigorously, we map the bit distributions to the Z Framework's discrete domain, instantiating DiscreteZetaShift objects with parameters derived from the bit length (a=256) and logarithmic invariants (b=e, c=e¬≤). Computations route through zeta chain unfolding and attribute extraction to derive curvatures \( \kappa \), which serve as proxies for pattern detection: low \( \kappa \) (e.g., <0.05) would indicate clustering or invariants, analogous to prime gaps.

### Analysis Approach
1. **Number Line Mapping**: Convert SHA-256 hashes to integers, representing the "number line." For inputs like sequential nonces, compute discrete derivatives as \( \delta_i = h_{i+1} - h_i \), where \( h_i \) is the integer hash value.
2. **Zeta Integration**: Seed DiscreteZetaShift with bit-related values (a=256), unfold the chain on derivatives, and extract attributes (e.g., F as curvature proxy via \( \theta'(n, 0.3) \)). This normalizes to \( Z = 256(\Delta_{256}/e^2) \), revealing potential invariants.
3. **Pattern Detection**: Evaluate curvatures for minima; high variance or consistent increase suggests randomness, while clustering would imply patterns.

Empirical simulation (reproducible via mpmath, dps=50) on 10 nonces yields hashes as ~10^{77} integers, with derivatives alternating in sign and magnitude (~10^{76}), confirming pseudorandom jumps. Zeta attributes: z‚âà94.18, D‚âà0.0289, E‚âà2.718, F‚âà0.358, G‚âà1.027, H‚âà0.349, I‚âà1.525. Unfolded curvatures (F) rise from 0.358 to 0.653, indicating escalating shifts without minima‚Äîconsistent with no exploitable patterns in SHA-256. For variants or truncated outputs, correlations exist (e.g., controlling half-bits), but full SHA-256 shows uniformity.

Hypothesis: In weakened hashes, zeta could cluster low-\( \kappa \) derivatives for pattern prediction, but for SHA-256, the framework substantiates cryptographic randomness via attribute dispersion.

_Originally posted by @zfifteen in https://github.com/zfifteen/unified-framework/issues/361#issuecomment-3193451247_

pull_request.body:
This PR implements the proposal to treat SHA-256 outputs (256-bit strings) as points on a number line and compute discrete derivatives to identify patterns using the Z Framework's discrete domain analysis, now including comprehensive academic analysis of the results.

## Key Features

**SHA-256 Number Line Mapping**: Converts 256-bit hash outputs to integers in the range [0, 2^256 - 1], enabling mathematical analysis of cryptographic outputs as discrete points.

**Discrete Derivative Computation**: Calculates differences between consecutive hash values (Œîh(i) = h(i+1) - h(i)) to detect potential patterns that deviate from expected randomness.

**Z Framework Integration**: Leverages the existing DiscreteZetaShift infrastructure with cryptographic parameters:
- a = 256 (SHA-256 bit length)
- b = e (natural logarithm base for logarithmic invariants) 
- c = e¬≤ (discrete domain normalization)

**Curvature-Based Pattern Detection**: Uses curvature Œ∫ computations as proxies for non-random behavior detection, where low curvature values may indicate structural patterns.

## Implementation Details

The core `SHA256PatternAnalyzer` class provides:

```python
from src.core import SHA256PatternAnalyzer

analyzer = SHA256PatternAnalyzer()

# Basic pattern analysis
results = analyzer.analyze_sequence("cryptographic_test", sequence_length=8)
print(f"Pattern detected: {results['pattern_metrics']['pattern_detected']}")

# Differential cryptanalysis
variants = ["message", "message1", "message_mod"]
diff_results = analyzer.detect_differential_patterns(variants)
print(f"Non-random behavior: {diff_results['differential_metrics']['non_random_behavior_detected']}")
```

## Validation & Analysis

- **Comprehensive test suite**: 13 tests covering all functionality, including SHA-256 avalanche effect validation
- **Mathematical correctness**: Proper integration with Z = n(Œî_n/Œî_max) discrete domain formula
- **High precision**: Uses mpmath with 50 decimal places for numerical stability
- **Performance verification**: Demonstrates good avalanche effect (55.5% bit changes for minimal input changes)

## Academic White Paper

Includes comprehensive academic analysis in `docs/SHA256_CRYPTOGRAPHIC_ANALYSIS_WHITEPAPER.md` that:

- **Analyzes experimental findings**: SHA-256 avalanche effect validation, consistent curvature patterns (Œ∫ ‚âà 0.38), discrete derivative ranges (~10^77)
- **Validates theoretical soundness**: Confirms Z Framework extends reliably to cryptographic applications
- **Identifies implications**: Novel cryptographic quality assessment metrics, geometric cryptographic analysis foundation
- **Outlines future research**: Framework extensibility to other hash functions, machine learning integration, blockchain analysis applications

## Applications

This implementation enables research into:
- Cryptographic hash pattern detection with mathematical rigor
- Differential cryptanalysis using discrete mathematics
- Statistical entropy assessment of hash sequences through curvature analysis
- Validation of Z Framework extensions to cryptographic domains
- Academic foundation for number-theoretic cryptanalysis

The approach aligns with differential cryptanalysis techniques by examining differences in outputs for non-random behaviors, while SHA-256's engineering for uniformity and resistance to such structure provides a robust test case for the discrete analysis framework.

With [SonarQube Cloud](https://sonarcloud.io/github), you get:
